Replace the ReportError stub for StoreReferenceInstruction in the kCC
output path with real emission, mirroring LoadReferenceInstruction.

* Tagged/smi path: emits
  `TaggedField<T>::store(UncheckedCast<HeapObject>(obj),
                         static_cast<int>(offset), value);`
  matching the corresponding TaggedField<T>::load call used by the
  existing Load path.
* Untagged path: emits `obj->WriteField<T>(offset, value);`
  matching the ReadField<T> call used by the existing Load path.

StoreReferenceInstruction, unlike LoadReferenceInstruction, does not
carry a FieldSynchronization field (Torque has no `@cppRelaxedStore` /
`@cppReleaseStore` decorators), so we only emit the plain
(release-barrier-free) store variants — the untagged path uses
WriteField rather than Relaxed_WriteField / Release_WriteField.

The debug (`is_cc_debug_`) path is rejected with ReportError: the
kCCDebug pipeline already uses READ_TAGGED_FIELD_OR_FAIL for loads,
but there is no pre-existing WRITE_* analogue, and no consumer in
Phase 2 needs it. Builtin-pointer types are still rejected via CHECK,
matching the CSA generator's protection.

This unblocks any Phase 2 fixture / real builtin whose body performs a
field write, provided the object + offset arrive on the stack as
runtime values. Classic extern-class field writes (`obj.field = v`)
would additionally require kCC support for the `%FromConstexpr` lowering
Torque emits for the field offset, which is an existing limitation
outside this task's scope.
